Heavy Fleet, Minibus, Plant, Boats and Associated Equipment
The maintenance of the heavy fleet (Lot 1) including fire appliances and associated equipment will generally include all vehicles over 3500kg GVW includes all pumping appliances, special appliances, aerial ladder platforms and a minibus. Light Fleet and Trailers

column67: Hammerton Greenway  Green Hammerton and Thorpe Underwood
column68:
It is proposed to construct a Greenway from Green Hammerton to Thorpe Underwood.  The village of Green Hammerton is located adjacent to the A59 between Harrogate and York.  A location plan of the route is shown heavily dotted on the map above.

The  1.7 km route will be suitable for cyclists, walkers, wheelchair and mobility scooter users. The surface will be durable all-weather crushed stone, up to 2m wide, with mown verges either side, giving a total width of 5m. The majority of the route will be an upgrade to existing farm track and public footpath; 2 sections, some 600m in total, create a new route. 

The route is established by two agreements: the 'Dedication of Public Highway: Creation of Cycletrack in the Parish of Green Hammerton', signed 2018 between North Yorkshire County Council, and two landowners whose tracks are crossed by the route, and the 'Public
Path Creation Agreement Pursuant to Section 30 of the Highways Act 1980' signed 2016 by Little Ouseburn, Kirby Hall and Thorpe Underwood Parish Council and Foxlow Ltd. Planning permission has been granted for the route by North Yorkshire Council. 

2. CLIENT 

The Client for the Works is Green Hammerton Parish Council.

3. OTHER PARTIES WITH AN INTEREST

North Yorkshire Council are funding the majority of the scheme from Developer Contributions arising from new housebuilding.  As such they have requirements on how the funds are managed and issued. The Internal Drainage Board have in interest insofar as the route crosses a beck and there are also concerns that the surface of the track should be sufficiently permeable to prevent excess run-off.

4. SCOPE OF WORK 

The length of construction is 1.726 km. The majority of the construction will be a 2.0m wide permeable stone surface. The material for the surface will be a type 3 material (with a 30% voids ratio), to be agreed with the Internal Drainage Board before commencement of work.   

A section of 178m of existing farm track at the south end is being optionally considered for bitmac surfacing or similar.  

Also included is the provision of a new timber preformed bridge over a beck. The bridge will be no more than 1.5m wide, and its design will be agreed in advance with the Internal Drainage Board.

Three piped ditch crossings will also be required, and three points on the Greenway will need appropriate reinforcement to allow tractors and other farm machinery to cross.

Post and plain wire fencing will be required where the route crosses one field. Other stretches may need to be fenced subject to discussion. Timber bollards will be required at the ends of the cycleway to prevent vehicular access.  

Some cutting back of overhanging branches and overgrown hedges will be necessary, and this work will need to be undertaken after the nesting season.

column67: GIS Programme - Regional Supplier Contract - Derbyshire
column68:
The Gigabit Infrastructure Subsidy programme, part of Project Gigabit, is a government programme aimed to support the build of gigabit-capable broadband infrastructure in the areas of the UK which are unlikely to attract commercial investment for gigabit-capable broadband infrastructure within a reasonable timeframe, if at all, referred to as the final 20% (f20). Building Digital UK (BDUK) will be targeting its market intervention in these areas of the UK via this subsidy award programme, to subsidise the build of gigabit-capable networks providing long-term, sustainable availability of wholesale gigabit broadband services in the hardest to reach parts of the UK. The Gigabit Infrastructure Subsidy programme builds on the success of existing programmes being delivered by BDUK to deliver gigabit-capable networks across the UK. It is envisaged this programme will last for up to 9 years and award contracts throughout that period. This contract is for the Derbyshire 3.0 intervention area.

Some documents that form part of this contract have not been included within the published document set as their entire contents are commercially sensitive.

column67: COAST Component A
column68:
Notice for the SQ stage of the Restricted Procedure for COAST Component A - COAST's aim is to improve the adaptive capacities, climate resilience and prosperity of vulnerable coastal communities, and drive a more sustainable and inclusive management of their marine environment and coastal resources.  To achieve this aim, COAST will focus on three outcome themes, based around areas with good underpinning evidence:   

protecting, restoring and sustainably managing coastal habitats and nature based solutions (e.g. mangroves, seagrass, corals)  

improving small scale fisheries' sustainability, productivity and resilience  

unlocking more sustainable, less intensive aquaculture.   

 

Component A will deliver integrated activities across COAST's themes at a range of scales through three sub-components. To maximise impact and scale, sub-components 1 and 2 will be focused in up to six priority countries, whilst flexibility will be retained in sub-component 3 to support activities in any ODA eligible country. This ITT is to appoint a Supplier to deliver this Component (Component A).

Additional information: 
To access the tender documents, please login or register to FCDO's eTendering Portal https://fcdo.bravosolution.co.uk. If you have any technical issues with the Portal, please call the eTendering helpdesk: +44 0203 868 2859 or use the "Call me Back!" functionality (recommended, especially if contacting from outside of UK). column67: NHS England Down's Syndrome Screening Quality Assurance Support Service (DQASS)
column68:
NHS England is to conduct market engagement to obtain input and feedback in preparation for a potential tender of a Down's Syndrome Screening Quality Assurance Support Service (DQASS) 

The Down's Syndrome Screening Quality Assurance Support Service (DQASS) is in place to monitor and support the quality and effectiveness of the screening tests for Down's syndrome (T21), Edwards' syndrome (T18) and Patau's syndrome (T13) in England.  
The DQASS service supports the NHS Fetal Anomaly Programme by providing statistical services that delivers independent clinical audit data and feedback to screening laboratories and ultrasound practitioners to enable quality assurance and continuous quality improvement.  
 
The analysis undertaken by the service checks the baseline median values, risk algorithm parameter values and population measures, such as age adjusted follow-up rates. Through meta-analyses,DQASSprovides information on effects of factors such as smoking that is used to improve screening performance. 
 
The analyses provided byDQASSis used by theScreening Quality Assurance Service (SQAS) to improve the screening programme through feedback on all aspects of the test to laboratories, ultrasound departments and commercial. 
DQASS provides independent audits of screening laboratory and ultrasound data in a standardised and statistically valid format.  
The service model includes statisticians who are experts in Down's, Edwards' and Patau's syndromes.  
For more detailed information about the DQASS, including reporting, please visit:  https://www.gov.uk/guidance/downs-syndrome-screening-quality-assurance-support-service

column68:
The provision of Suicide Prevention Training to Hampshire County Council and partner organisation in line with the Hampshire and Isle of Wight (HIOW) Integrated Care System (ICS) footprint which targets frontline professionals and provides skills in managing one-off suicidal conversations, enabling people to signpost on to appropriate services. 

The training provided, provides a therapeutic framework and the  tools to work with a client on an ongoing basis in managing their suicidal ideation. This has been identified by partners as a gap, via local Suicide Prevention Forums and Partnerships across the ICS.

CAMS (Collaborative Assessment and Management of Suicidality) training is based on the work and research led by Dr. David Jobes and is based on suicide risk being treatable and works to address the drivers that make someone want to die by suicide.

Additional information: The CAMS Care Therapy can only be provided by this licensed practitioner and training organisation. This arrangement is valued below the UK procurement threshold and a waiver of Contract Standing Orders has been applied to utilise this unique bespoke Suicide Prevention Training Sessions.

column67: Public Realm Works -  North Commercial Road, Future High Streets - AWARD
column68:
Portsmouth City Council - the 'council' - is inviting expressions of interest from suitably qualified and experienced suppliers for the provision of the delivery of public realm improvement works at Commercial Road Portsmouth. 
      
      The aim of the project is to create an attractive, safe and enjoyable place for people to meet, rest or spend time while they are in the city centre. The interventions will help to support longer dwell times in the city centre, discourage anti-social behaviour and improve people's confidence in and perceptions of this area.  We are looking for contractors to implement the proposed works comprising of turning hard tree pits into planting, install new seating, play equipment and associated play surface at top end of Commercial Road in Portsmouth. 
      
      The council is targeting to have awarded the contract by 9th October 2023 to allow for commencement on 8th January 2024 and completion no later than 15th March 2024 in accordance with external grant funding conditions
      
      The value of the contract requirement equates to between approximately ?250,000 to ?300,000 and this is based upon design activities and surveys to date. 
      
      The council will undertake a procurement process to award the contract in line with the summary programme set out below;
      
      o Project published on Contracts Finder - Tuesday 6th June 2023
      o SSQ and procurement documents published on Intend - Tuesday 6th June 2023
      o Deadline for requests for clarification - Sunday 25th June 2023 at 23:59
      o SSQ submission deadline - Wednesday 5th July 2023 at 12:00
      o Notification of SSQ evaluation results - Monday 17th July 2023
      o ITT and final procurement documents published on In-tend - Tuesday 8th August 2023
      o Deadline for requests for clarification - Friday 1st September at 23:59
      o Tender return deadline - Friday 15th September at 12:00
      o Notification of preferred bidder - Monday 2nd October 2023
      o Target contract execution - Monday 9th October 2023
      o Works commencement - Monday 8th January 2024
      
      Application is via completion and submission of a project specific Supplier Status Questionnaire (SSQ) and associated further documentation by Friday 30th June 2023 at 12:00
      
      Following assessment of SSQ submissions a maximum of six suppliers that meet all minimum requirements will be invited to tender. In the event that multiple suppliers are tied at 6th place through the achievement of identical scores then only the top 5 will be taken through.

column67: PQ0492 - cardiovascular disease (CVD) public health campaign 2024
column68:
The cardiovascular disease (CVD) campaign is a gold-tier Public Health campaign which will support the cardiovascular health awareness efforts currently being delivered by the Million Hearts Programme pilot operated by BSOL ICS.
      
      The Provider will run a campaign to increase public engagement with the ongoing Million Hearts Programme (MHP). It is a community engagement initiative which targets Birmingham residents at risk of hypertension and signposts them to primary care practitioners for support with managing the condition. MHP also hands out free blood pressure monitors to residents who may be at-risk of developing hypertension.
      The provider will be tasked with planning, negotiating, and executing a comprehensive local marketing campaigns to maximise our reach and engagement within the targeted demographic groups (i.e. BAME residents, with a focus on people of black African and black Caribbean heritage) as well as the wider public as part of an overall effort to raise awareness of the issue of hypertension and the associated dangers.
      
      The city council has a maximum budget of 30,000 to undertake this work and a fixed price submission is expected to cover all costs including expenses associated with delivery of the outcomes set out in the quotation document available to download as follows.
      
      
      The Council will be using its free to use e-tendering system (in-tend) for the administration of this procurement process and potential suppliers must register with the system to be able to express an interest. If you wish to express an interest in this opportunity please click on the following link to access https://in-tendhost.co.uk/birminghamcc/ and submit your details to register. You will then be able to login and download all relevant quotation documentation.

column67: A Framework Agreement for the Provision of Independent Fostering Agency (IFA) Services
column68:
This procurement invites tenders from both new applicants to The Councils' Framework for the Provision of Independent Fostering Agencies (IFA) Services, or from existing providers on this framework who wish to improve their original price offers or to apply for a place on additional lots.

The notice for the original establishment of the Framework Agreement was published on the 28th July 2021 (reference 2021/S 000-017949) and the amended publication dated 7th September 2021, reference 2021/S 000-022124) which read as follows: 

"This procurement is for the establishment of a framework agreement for the provision of independent fostering agency services across sixteen (16) local authorities that comprise the South-Central IFA Framework consortium. This ITT is to establish a Framework Agreement between Southampton City Council (on behalf of the South-Central IFA Framework consortium) and those tenderers successful in their applications to be accepted on to the framework to enable the provision of foster care placements in accordance with the terms of the framework agreement. The consortium have the following needs from independent fostering agency placements:
Foster carers for children of all ages, but particularly for older children aged 10-15 years. Foster carers who can meet higher levels of need, complexity and risk. 
Foster carers who can care for sibling groups - particularly large sibling groups.    
Foster carers who care for parent and child placements
Foster carers who can care for disabled children- especially with adapted homes. Some will have complex medical needs and some may have a limited life expectancy.    
Foster carers who are registered for only one child to meet the need for solo placements.
Foster carers who can care for Unaccompanied Asylum Seekers and with an awareness/willingness to work in partnership to meet their immediate immigration, health and educational needs.
In addition, the Councils are particularly looking for local, well-matched placements, including education provision, and with commitment to the best interests of the child.     
Enhanced fostering care placements for children and young people with higher levels of need.
The Framework is comprised of the following 4 Lots:
Lot 1 (Standard Placements 0+ Years) 
Lot 2 (Children with Disabilities)
Lot 3 (Parent and Child Placements)
Lot 4 (Enhanced Fostering  Placements)  
Providers may bid for one or more of these Lots in any combination.
This is a requirement amongst some of the consortium members for foster placements that may be located with Wales. As such providers of fostering services based in Wales in addition to those in England are welcome to tender.

Additional information: The procurement is to continue establishing a framework agreement with an initial term of four years with 21 months remaining. 

There is the option to extend the framework agreement by up to two additional twelve month periods, i.e. from 1st April 2026 - 31st March 2027 and from 1st April 2027- 31st March 2028.

column67: MLB - Ofsted Children's Residential Home in County Durham
column68:
Ofsted Registered Solo / Small Bedded Children's Residential Home required in County Durham.

Placement required for 16 year old Male within the North East. MLB has a diagnosis of ASD and is currently subject to a DOLS requiring 3:1 staffing to meet his needs. 

MLB is a lovely, friendly young person. He is very sociable, chatty, and outgoing. He loves football, bikes, buses and his nana and grandad very much. His favourite football team is Newcastle United and he is often seen wearing different football kits regardless of the weather. MLB likes to socialise with other young people and he will seek to build friendships and relationship with his carers and workers also. MLB thrives on social interactions and this helps him to feel settled. MLB has a good sense of humour and will often make jokes and chit-chat with people when he meets people. 

MLB also enjoys playing on his Xbox, he will arrange to play online with friends on Fortnite. MLB likes to take care of his appearance, he will spend around 1-2 hours each morning getting ready and he has a large collection of aftershave, something he enjoys wearing. MLB will often wear sportswear and often looks smart and neat. 

MLB not only enjoys watching football and following his favourite teams, but he also loves playing football. He will play football in the back garden at his home, at the park and he goes to a football club once a week where he plays in an over sixteen team. MLB is a talented footballer and this is something he enjoys pursuing. 

MLB is a keen leaner; he has told the social worker how much he wants to go to school and that he wants to go to college when he is older. He is currently having home tuition while we search for a school place for him and he enjoys this and works well with his tutors, he is working towards his foundations level 1 in Maths and English. 

MLB has had quite a lot of placements in the past as he struggled to settle into being in care. MLB was initially placed in the Local Authority's care after his grandparents signed a Section 20 for his as they felt they could not keep him safe at home. MLB was extremely upset by this as he believed he would shortly be returning to their care; however, this became a long-term situation as grandparents did not feel they could have him back. This led MLB to having lots of homes over a short period of time as when he is unsettled, the number of aggressive incidents is increased. When living in southern England, MLB was unhappy that he was away from his home area and frequently tried to return. Since coming back to the north East in July 2023, he has been much calmer and more stable. There have been very few aggressive incidents, no incidents of harmful sexual behaviour and only two missing episodes, this is a massive improvement.

If you are interested in receiving tenders for future opportunities directly and join our off-framework list, please contact ahs.commissioning@durham.gov.uk for further information.

column67: Forum Tower - Masonry Removal
column68:
Westmorland and Furness Council requested WSP to complete a scope for intrusive works to the stair core known as the Forum Tower in the North-West corner of the Forum Building.
The building including stair core was constructed in the late 1960's and comprises a steel frame with masonry walls. The steel frame is encased in concrete over the lower levels. A concrete staircase and lift shaft are contained within the core and there are flat concrete slabs at roof level.
WSP and others have undertaken visual surveys of the structure generally and identified that water ingress and cracking is present throughout the masonry outer leaf, with significant corrosion to the steel frame within the masonry cavity, which may be leading to some of the masonry cracking, known as Regent Street Disease.
Intrusive work to remove masonry from the Forum Tower are now required to establish the full extent of defects to the steelwork, and specification of remedial repairs required to the steel structure, followed by rebuilding.
It is currently unclear whether the roof top car park will be retained as a car park or changed to maintenance only, however it is understood that the fire strategy requires all staircases to the roof top car park to remain, therefore the tower should be rebuilt once repairs or replacement are completed to maintain access to all levels.
A fee proposal to undertake remedial works by the contractor is now sought for the client's consideration.

column67: Mobile Locational Analytics Data 2024
column68:
1.3    Description of scope/Specification
      
      1. Historic England is looking to purchase data collected through mobile platforms and other digital hardware to produce research for the Cultural Heritage Capital Programme (CHC). We need data for informed decision-making using locational analytics from mobile devices and other sources. The successful candidate will provide data and insights on movement patterns, visitor frequency, dwell time, and where visitors are residentially from.
      
      2. The research aims to explore the use of data from mobile devices and other sources for alternative sampling methods in economic valuation. The collected data will be used for econometric analysis and descriptive statistics.
      
      3. There must be scope for 15 separate heritage sites to be analysed. More will be preferred. Essential data on movement patterns, visitor frequency and where visitors are residentially from should be available for at least 5 heritage sites when the contract start date. All heritage sites will be expected within 28 calendar days of the starting date. If availability exists to change these locations afterwards, such time limits will not contain them.
      
      4. The successful candidate will be awarded up to ?50,000 (including VAT) for the services pretraining to this tender. Not all of this funding must be used. If a candidate suggests a bid above ?50,000 the bid will automatically be disregarded. The price of the service will be considered as part of the 'Most Economically Advantageous Tender'. The award criteria in full can be seen in full in section 3.1.
      
      Data:
      
      5. Historic England must be able to use the data for aggregated and statistical analysis purposes. The findings from the statistical analysis will be published. Graphical representations of aggregated data may be published.
      
      6. Data should be provided in forms which allow further manipulation (e.g. SPSS, CSV or Execl files). Any additional mapping or access to software would also be welcome. Data will be shared internally within the organisation.
      
      7. The successful candidate must provide details on how long access to the data will be provided and how far back data can be viewed. The platform must also provide information on how quickly new data will be updated.
      
      Required Data -
      
      8. Failing to provide the required data will result in automatic withdrawal of the tender.
      
      9. The number of visitors: This data is necessary to understand how many visitors are visiting a defined geographical area of the researcher's choice.
      
      10. Visitor origin data (minimum MSOA level or equivalent geographical region): This data provides information on where visitors are coming from.
      
      11. We will require at least 1 year of data for each site. The methodological approach of collecting data must allow us to see what has happened for at least one year prior to the award of this contract.
      
      Optional Data:
      
      12. Optional data is not...

Additional information: 
Suppliers interested in this opportunity should register at https://in-tendhost.co.uk/historicengland/aspx/Home in order to express interest and download documentation.

Is a Recurrent Procurement Type? : No

column67: CS 24 01 East Midlands Regional Collaboration Support - Soft Market Testing
column68:
THIS IS NOT A CALL FOR COMPETITION 
 
Derbyshire County Council are seeking to ascertain the supply base for a collaboration partner to support the East Midlands and Northamptonshire Childrens Trust (NCT). The intention is to understand the number of suppliers that are available to meet our requirements, the value the support could demonstrate, and the cost of doing business with them. All ten local authorities in the East Midlands and NCT are committed to the principles behind sector led improvement and have formed the East Midlands Regional Improvement and Innovation Alliance (RIIA). We believe that it is our responsibility to ensure the services we provide and the approaches we take are rooted in ensuring that outcomes for children, young people and their families are improved. The Alliance is built upon openness and trust and will serve to provide robust support and challenge and a programme of joint learning and development against clear priorities. 
 
Instructions for Participation

Suppliers are invited to complete the questionnaire.  In addition, the attached Identification of Confidential Information (FOIA Schedule) must also be completed and returned. 

All completed documents must be returned via the Proactis e-tendering portal by Tuesday 13th February 2024 12pm.

Where we think further clarification is required, we may seek further discussion with those potential suppliers who submit a response as part of this exercise.  

For the avoidance of doubt no information provided in response to this questionnaire will be used by the Council in assessing providers during any procurement process. Information will be used for gathering market intelligence only. 
 
All information included in this Soft Market Testing questionnaire is confidential and only for the recipient's knowledge. No information included in this document or in discussions connected to it may be disclosed to any other party without prior written authorisation.

column67: MA17 - Site Investigation & Anchoring for FOW
column68:
One challenge for the deployment of Floating Offshore Wind Turbines (FOWTs) is designing and installing anchors that are both reliable and cost-effective, whilst being capable of withstanding the dynamic loads exerted by the mooring lines. 

Site investigation is a critical stage in the design of these anchors. It gives vital data on seabed geology, soil properties, and environmental conditions, all of which influence the choice of anchor type, its performance, and the installation method. 
The site investigation for offshore anchors typically encompasses a mix of geophysical and geotechnical surveys. The specific methods and equipment used are dictated by the characteristics of the site in question.

column67: Inductive Coupled Plasma Optical Emission Spectrometry - AWARD
column68:
The University of Warwick has a requirement to purchase an inductive coupled plasma optical emission spectrometer (ICP-OES) for trace element analysis. 
      
      A high performance ICP-OES system is required to replace our existing obsolete ICP-OES system to carry out metal/semi-metal elements quantitation analysis in the Department of Chemistry (University of Warwick). The instrument will be used primarily for the analysis of complex samples with a variety of background/matrix from biological and synthetic studies. Due to extremely low metal content in many biological samples and very large concentration range observed, high sensitivity (low ppb (<10) for majority of metal elements) and high dynamic range are essential. The ability to handle high matrix content in sample introduction and an auto-sampler that can accommodate different sample vials (from 2ml to 50ml, tray that can load up to 200 samples) are also required. 
      
      In order to express interest in this opportunity please go to the University of Warwick In-Tend supplier portal (https://in-tendhost.co.uk/universityofwarwick).
      
      The University of Warwick is not a contracting authority for the purposes of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (as amended) and its procurement activities are not subject to the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 or the obligations under the European Public Procurement Directives, including the European Remedies Directive. Advertisement of any contract in the Official Journal of the European Union or Contracts Finder is at the sole discretion of the University and is undertaken on a voluntary basis with no implied obligation to comply with the procurement legislation.

Supported housing is defined as self-contained accommodation with low level support delivered on site. 
Supported Housing for disability is utilised for people with a learning disability and people with autistic needs. 

This opportunity is to supply up to 37 units of self-contained accommodation units, with onsite support, within the Borough of Swindon. This may be provided in more than one building but the following criteria must apply:
	Must provide one communal front door, communal laundry, communal garden and office space.  
	Must provide members of staff relevant to the amount of units offer to provide both housing management and housing related support.
	Must be available by the 1st April 2024

The initial contract term will be for 36 months with an option to extend for a further 12 months for a potential total contract term of 4 years as stated in the ITT documents. Lot 2: Emergency Hormonal Contraception (EHC):

Lot 3: Nicotine Replacement Therapy:

We look forward to receiving your proposals and partnering with you to deliver high-quality pharmacy services that benefit the community of Leicestershire.

column66: WNC CL Environmental Monitoring and Technical service
column67: Provision of Environmental Monitoring and Technical and Professional Service 4 x Closed Landfill Sites Situated within the Geographical Region of West Northamptonshire Council
column68:
West Northamptonshire Council is seeking quotations for a service to provide professional and technical support on both define projects and routine operations via environmental monitoring to 4 closed landfill sites within the geographical region of West Northamptonshire. 

West Northamptonshire Council (WNC) has a statutory duty to manage 4 of these closed landfill sites.  Not all the sites are owned by WNC, however under the legislation the statutory duties and liabilities sit with WNC.  These former landfill sites were constructed using "dilute and disperse" principles with very little information regarding how the sites were engineered or what type of wastes were deposited.

The approach taken to managing these sites is predominantly planned and prudent (avoiding unnecessary costs) however there is expected that an element of additional technical support required due to review of the routine environmental monitoring data/site conditions potential for on-site systems having operational issues/failure.  

The Council accepts that these sites present risks and although the risks are mitigated, they will always remain.  Work is undertaken to investigate and understand the risks posed has helped the Council understand which sites present the most significant risks.

The Council is therefore looking for a Service Provider to provide professional and technical support to both defined projects and routine operations via environmental monitoring to the closed landfill sites.

There are currently 4 closed landfill sites for which West Northants Council (WNC) has liabilities:
	Gayton Landfill (and associated Leachate Treatment Plant)
	Dodmoor Farm Closed Landfill 
	Farthinghoe Closed Landfill
	Woodford Halse Closed Landfill

These sited do not have any engineered containment, nor do they have gas extractions and only Gayton Closed Landfill site has a leachate/management extraction system and on-site treatment plant (operated by others). 

The are 2 main work streams that WNC will require technical support are; 
1.	Environmental Monitoring and reporting - 4 sites 
2.	Technical Support - at any or all of the 4 sites required on an adhoc request for quote basis 

The work streams interrelate but not duplicate.

If you would like to be considered for this contract, please e-mail alice.haines@westnorthants.gov.uk to request the Request for Quotation document, detailing the Council's requirement and instructions for taking part and responding. Please note the response deadline is no later than 12:00pm 19th February 2024. 

We look forward to receiving your submission and in the event of any queries or requests for further information arising from this Request for Quotation, please contact us by e-mail, at alice.haines@westnorthants.gov.uk

The National Physical Laboratory (NPL) requirement is for two multi-channel radiofrequency (RF) phase comparators suitable for comparing hydrogen maser derived 10 MHz signals for all averaging times. The first is for the determination of any uncertainty introduced by time and frequency transfer over several coaxial cables and optical fibre links. While the second is for comparisons between state-of-the-art optically steered time scales against the UK time scale UTC (NPL) and several other H-maser signals.

The phase comparators need to be able to measure multiple RF signals simultaneously without introducing significant phase instability into the measurement.

column67: CEFAS23-137 Contract for Quotation for LA-ICP-MS analysis on fish otoliths
column68:
As part of the "Improving methodology to assess finfish, pelagic, data-limited, and non-quota stocks to inform management advice." project under the WP2.5 "Assessment of otolith microchemistry (e.g., plaice and sole, herring, sprat, sardine and horse mackerel)" Cefas are seeking a suitable supplier to conduct otolith microchemistry analysis via Laser Ablation-Inductively Coupled Plasma-Mass Spectrometer (LA-ICP-MS) for tracing several elements (Li6,Li7, Na23, Mg24, Ca43, Ca44, Mn55, Co59, Cu63, Cu65, Zn66, Rb85, Sr86, Sr87, Sr88, Cd112, Ba138, Ba137, Pb208, Pb207) of the above-mentioned species.

For the purpose of the research and quality control, Cefas request the use of specific calibration standards including NIST610, NIST612, NIST614, MACS-1 and, more importantly, otolith-specific standards such as FEBS-1 and Nies 22. We require a continuous transect core-to-edge otolith sampling design for each otolith with the ability to easily isolate the core-only and edge-only transects for specific analysis. Ablation patterns including laser size, length, speed and other variables will be discussed as a species-by-species case.

Cefas will be providing samples embedded in glass slides (pelagic species) and in plastic strips (flatfish species). Technical meetings with the WP leader (either via Teams or in presence) will be required for a) the provision of samples to be analysed and b) delivery of data from analysis and return of samples to Cefas.

One month time frame will be required for the Cefas WP leader to check the quality of delivered data.

The successful supplier is expected to have access to LA-ICP-MS equipment and clear capability to support for the required analysis of the above-mentioned species, including availability for the time needed to run the analysis for each species (previous experience working and handling fish otolith preparations is essential).

Cefas will be responsible for arranging the collection and delivery of samples throughout the project via our preferred courier services. It is the expectation of Cefas that the Supplier/s will abide to our expectations for sample return, which will be discussed at kick off meeting.

Data:
The results need to be presented as final (including quality controls and technical details on the method), in the form of an Excel file (.csv) providing clear element concentration (calibrated) for each otolith, and ready to be statistically analysed (e.g., no further adjustment against blanks etc.).

column67: Bolsover Skills to Thrive 19+
column68:
Bolsover District faces social and economic challenges that include a prevalence of low paid work in low productivity sectors such as retail, warehousing and some parts of the health and social care sector; and high levels of area deprivation with nearly half of all areas (46%) in Bolsover being in the 20% most deprived nationally in relation to the Education, Skills and Training domain.  Poor connectivity by public transport to locations where jobs are concentrated, especially where employment growth is driven by significant out of town retail and distribution centres is also a challenge.
      Although the pandemic has not generated the high levels of unemployment initially expected, there are groups disproportionately impacted including younger workers, the low paid and, some Black and Minority Ethnic (BAME) groups, and those with disabilities or health conditions. Moreover, there is evidence that jobs in some sectors including retail, hospitality and leisure remain below pre-pandemic levels despite the national boom in vacancies, with displaced workers moving into unemployment or inactivity rather than growing sectors such as health and social care. This indicates a skill mismatch which may be further exacerbated by changes in working patterns as a shift towards more hybrid forms of working penalise some without the space, access to technology or digital skills to embrace new opportunities.

Additional information: 
The Authority is using the In-tend e-tendering portal to conduct the procurement process ('the e-Tendering Portal'). The e-Tendering Portal can be accessed. https://in-tendhost.co.uk/Bolsoverdc all communications (including submission of Tenders) should be carried out via the e-Tendering Portal.

This procurement is being concluded following a mini competition under the Crown Commercial Services - Space-Enabled and Geospatial Services - RM6235

Brief Description of Requirement

The UKSA/MOD are seeking to partner with reliable and proven SST data suppliers, with extensive knowledge of space domain awareness, to procure SST data. This supplementary sensor data will be combined with current data sources to improve UK SST capability.

The UKSA/MOD seeks to procure SST data which is:

	High quality: accurate data on the position, velocity or trajectory of space objects 
	Timely: responsive sensor collection to data delivery time. 
	Assured: persistent observations and high data availability per object.

The procurement is separated across 2 Civil Lots as follows:

-	Lot 1: SST data in higher earth orbits (HO)
-	Lot 2: SST data in lower earth orbits (LEO)

Each Lot comprises of:
-	Routine List-Based Tasking to track UK licensed RSO (Core)
-	Event-Based Tasking to track UK licensed RSO or secondary space objects posing a hazard to UK RSO. (Optional)

column66: 2 Solar pumps RSPB Old Hall marshes_Jan 2024
column67: 2 Solar water pumps RSPB Old Hall Marshes
column68:
The RSPB has secured funding from the Natural England Species Recovery Project to carry out works to improve the habitats found at RSPB Old Hall Marshes.

RSPB Old Hall Marshes is a 465 ha area of grazing marsh, reedbed, borrowdykes, saltmarsh and intertidal mudflats located in the Blackwater Estuary, Essex. The reserve has several designations ranging from national to international.  It is a National Nature Reserve (NNR), Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI), Special Protection Area (SPA), Special Area of Conservation (SAC) and Ramsar. These designations have been awarded both to Old Hall Marshes and to the Blackwater and Essex Estuaries for a range of wildlife features including internationally important numbers of wintering waders and wildfowl, the range of salt marsh plant and invertebrate species, and scarce breeding bird species such as redshank and pochard.

This project will see the supply and installation of two solar powered pump units and solar panels, that will be used to manage water levels in a saline lagoon. 

This project will help achieve suitable wet conditions to benefit breeding birds such as Avocet and Common tern, and other wetland wildlife and is part of a larger project that seeks to reduce dependence on Diesel pumps to move water around the reserve and continue the reserves journey toward a degree of climate resilience. 

This tender is for the supply of the Solar powered water pumps, there is a separate tender for the associated earthworks required to install the solar pump.

Additional information: See Invitation to Tender for more details

column67: WCC Data Governance System
column68:
Warwickshire Country Council is looking to re procure its Data Governance System (DGS) contract. 
The DGS acts as the Council's Record of Processing (RoPA), which we are obliged to maintain under the UK GDPR/Date Protection Act 2018 to map all data flows containing Personal and Special Category personal data.  We have incorporated the RoPA, Data Protection Impact Assessments (DPIA) and our Information Asset Register which also covers assets that do not process personal information, in order to capture all assets, data flows, Sharing Agreements and Risk Assessments in one place. 

The web address is: https://in-tendhost.co.uk/csw-jets/aspx/Home.

Registration and use of In-Tend is free. Once registered, all correspondence for this procurement process must be via the in-tend correspondence function. However, if you are unable to register with the website please email us at procurement@warwickshire.gov.uk

Paradigm Housing Group (PHG) is seeking to contract with a single provider suitably qualified and experienced to deliver PHG's Grounds Maintenance Provision for all our sites where the service is required. 
PHG manages over 900 parcels of land blocks and estates, ranging in size and complexity across Buckinghamshire, Bedfordshire, Oxfordshire, Hertfordshire, Cambridgeshire and North and North-West London. 
The sites cover a range of types of land, including 
Formal-type gardens 
Informal gardens 
Amenity land 
Verges and green sward 
Wildflower gardens 
Meadowland 
Estate pathway 
Shared pathways (to rear entrances to houses) 
Public rights of way 
Woodland 
Hedges 
Roads 
Recent inspections and audits of existing stock have identified that investment is needed in its grounds.  Whilst site improvements do not form part of this contract, we want to work with The Contractor to identify improvements and develop a plan for improving the external areas of estates. 
The approximate spend is 1,000,000 per annum. 
Transfer of Undertakings Protection of Employment Regulations 2006 (TUPE) may apply to this opportunity. 
The contract start date will be 1st April 2024 for 4 years with the option at the discretion of Paradigm, subject to performance and available budget, to extend for a further 3, one year periods (i.e. 1+1+1).

Supplier registration (due-north.com)

column68:
Hillingdon Council is seeking a suitably experienced contractor to deliver (as the sole main-contractor) a programme of kitchen replacements and/or bathroom replacements over an agreed programme period for circa 73 occupied domestic dwellings in various wards, Hillingdon. (40 Kitchens & 40 Bathrooms & 10 Seperate WC's).

The proposed contract will be based upon a pre-determined basket of rates developed using the National Housing Maintenance Forum M3NHF Schedule of Rates version 7.1 including its long descriptions, the specifications of workmanship and materials and the relevant SOR (schedules of rates) rates for each element of the required works. The rates are to include for all preliminaries, overheads, and profits. As part of their tender submission, contractors are required to tender a single percentage increase or deduction adjustment to these basket rates as stipulated in the Pricing Schedule and enter this adjustment into the Basket Rate Adjustment Tab.

The proposed contract will be for a period of approximately 16-20 weeks or as agreed with the successful Contractor.

The Council has concluded a selection process to identify our preferred Kitchen Supplies provider.  All bidding Contractors must purchase kitchen items required to complete the installations from Howdens Joinery Ltd using Hillingdon's pre agreed rates.

column67: Bletchley Leisure Centre - Lease Opportunity
column68:
Bletchley Leisure Centre (BLC) is a popular leisure centre situated in the south of the city which serves the whole community of Milton Keynes. The facility is well used by the public and a wide range of sports clubs and community groups in and around Milton Keynes. BLC is Milton Keynes City Councils largest leisure facility comprising of:
      
      o 25m 8 lane Swimming Pool with Spectator Viewing
      o 7 Rink Bowls Hall
      o 6 Badminton Court Multi Use Sports Hall
      o 4 Squash Courts with Viewing Facilities (with moveable wall to create a double court space)
      o 100 Station Fitness Suite (including E-gym equipment)
      o 2 x Multi Use Aerobic Studio
      o Sauna and Steam Room
      o Multi-Purpose Suite 
      o Caf? Servery and Seating Area
      o Foyer, Reception and Office Accommodation
      o Associated Changing Rooms
      o Multi Storey Car Park
      o Spin Studio
      o 2 x Physio rooms
      
      Milton Keynes City Council are in the process of consolidating the leisure offer for the city and are looking to implement a 16 month fully repairing lease agreement with a suitably experienced organisation to operate the site from 1st November 2024 to 28th February 2026
      
      However, to help the council understand the market please can you, as part of the expression of interest, provide a response to the following question:

column67: Digital Skills Courses
column68:
Skills Connect is West Yorkshire Combined Authorities' fully-funded, non-accredited adult training programme. It offers flexible courses at an equivalent to Level 3 and above and has been developed to address employer skills shortages within the region., allowing individuals to access higher level employment opportunities or progression within their current employment.

Courses offer innovative delivery methods, blending the acquisition of specialist skills with more holistic wrap-around and careers information, advice and guidance (CIAG) support, which meets the needs of individuals and businesses.

All courses are delivered at an equivalent to Level 3 and above and content is created in response to employers' needs. Courses can be delivered online, in-person or a blend of both in order to best suit the needs of participants and training requirements. In addition, training is delivered flexibly to ensure that participants with employment, family or other commitments can access the opportunity to upskill.

Events will encourage residents and visitors to the high street to shop locally and increase dwell time.
      
      Events will be delivered before the 31st March 2025 within each high street.   It is anticipated that delivery can take place in the Spring/early Summer for Crowborough, Hailsham, Heathfield and Uckfield with a later event in Polegate in March 2025.  The Polegate event will aim to be a celebration of the overall UK SPF programme which will also see improvements to the Cuckoo Trail.

column67: Sixpenny Handley Skatepark Upgrade
column68:
Sixpenny Handley and Pentridge Parish Council is seeking to appoint a single Contractor to Design & Build a skatepark facility for the Local Community.  
The existing Skatepark is in a multi activity area (Basketball Hoop) sharing a tarmac area. There is a metal and wood constructed half pipe which needs replacing. The Parish Council can make adjacent land available to connect with this area to allow for a wider ranging skatepark to be constructed.
There is an existing project team which includes young people who participate in Skateboarding, the applicant will engage with this team to design, plan and build the replacement skatepark. Funding will be through grants; the applicant is expected to support the project team in obtaining grant funding and once obtained complete the building of the skatepark.
To apply for this contract please complete the attached procurement document (Sixpenny Handley Skatepark Upgrade tender application .docx).

- make contact to arrange site visits if needed
- submit clarification questions by the deadline indicated

The project team are holding a design shaping session on 23 Jan and will publish the output from this session as an additional document.

Submission and contract dates have been adjusted by 1 month to accommodate this update.

column67: Transforming Organisations, Partnerships, and Systems
column68:
East of England NHS Collaborative Procurement Hub (EoECPH) is seeking to award a framework for Transforming Organisations, Partnerships & Systems - Multi-Speciality Support & Advisory Consultancy Services.

Additional information: 
EoECPH wishes to provide support to the NHS and the wider arena of publicly funded services with the provision of innovative transformation and consultancy services to assist them in meeting system challenges they face, both now and in the future. 

The purpose of this procurement is to secure service providers who will support Contracting Authorities of publicly funded entities meet requirements set against them in pursuit of their day-to-day activities, as well as organisational and service transformation, redesign, and modelling, within the constantly evolving landscape of public/person centric services. Suppliers awarded to the framework will assist Contracting Authorities to manage and meet obligations and other pressures which impact and have relevance to publicly funded organisations, helping them adhere to current and future legislative and best practice requirements concerning their service delivery.

Core lot titles for the Framework include:
Lot 1	Sustainable Services Modelling, Design & Improvement
Lot 2	Strategy, System Leadership, Governance, & Integrated Assurance
Lot 3	Training, Quality Assurance and Consultation Services
Lot 4	Commercial, Financial and Analytical Related Advisory Services
Lot 5	Procurement and Supply Chain Services  
Lot 6 	Workforce Transformation  
Lot 7	Communications and Engagement Delivery
Lot 8	Multi-Disciplinary Consultancy Services

The Contracting Authority intends to use Atamis as the e-Procurement Portal in this procurement exercise.

https://atamis-1928.1ightning.force.com/

Deadline for submission of bids is 23rd February 2024 at 12pm.

column67: GB-Shrewsbury: ROCB 027 - Maintenance and Repair of Convector Heaters and Night Storage Heaters
column68:
This is a contract award notice for the Council to discharge their responsibility of the inspection, testing, certification and repair works of the following life safetysystems at Shropshire Council Properties along with those of other external clientsto the Council: 
      Convector / Fan assisted Heaters. 
      Inspection, maintenance, and cleaning of convector/ fan assisted heating equipment in line with the manufacturers' recommendations, The IET Code of Practice for In-service Inspection and Testing of Electrical Equipment, BS7671 and the Servicing Schedule - Appendix A.
      
      A before and after cleaning photograph to be included within the service report along with the date and time photo was taken.
      Off Peak/ night Storage heaters.
      Inspection, maintenance and cleaning of convector/ fan assisted heating equipment in line with the manufacturers' recommendations, The IET Code of Practice for In-service Inspection and Testing of Electrical Equipment, BS7671 and the Servicing Schedule - Appendix A.
      
      A before and after cleaning photograph to be included within the service report along with the date and time photo was taken.
      
      The works indicated above shall enable the Council to demonstrate compliance with the relevant sections of the RRO(Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005). 
       
      These visits to be within the months shown in the Schedule of Properties - Schedule 2 and shall not lapse the date given. Inspections are permitted to be undertaken up to 2 weeks early. 
      
      TheContract shall comprise of the remedial works requiredto repair the existing equipment if found to be faultysubject to the prior approval of the Budget Holder and Counciland shall be in accordance with clause2.11 
       
      Duration of the Contract
      Fixed price tenders are being invited to the period 1st April 2024 - 31st March 2027. Thereafter, the contract may be extended for up to a further two years (up to 31st March 2029) subject to satisfactory performance during the term of the contract year and the agreement of the costs for the ensuing 24 months.
      
      Prices submitted are for the period of 1st April 2024 - 31st March 2027 thereafter the contractor may submit a cost adjustment to the tendered figure for the potential 24 months extension that is in line with the Consumer Price Index for the previous calendar year period as defined on the ONS website under the "CPI All Item: percentage change of 12 months data series", and which is subject to the approval by the Council. However, in any event, the Council reserves the right to negotiate with the Contractor any proposed increase in rate if in its opinion they are not justified.

Additional information: The contracting authority considers that this contract may be suitable for economic operators that are small or medium enterprises (SMEs). However, any selection of tenderers will be based solely on the criteria set out for the procurement.

column67: Provision of Graduate Recruitment Service
column68:
The key services to be provided are:
The Succes  undertake a full search process for all our graduate pathways including but not limited to the following aspects:
-	Drafting an attraction campaign strategy for each pathway, to be presented within a week of contract execution
-	The brief should outline how and where roles are to be advertised, 
-	the universities reached, 
-	activities on campus focused on Ofcom roles (if any), 
-	how Ofcom as a brand is sold to candidates, 
-	Review and refresh attraction content and materials on an annual basis
-	Running the attraction campaign for each pathway once reviewed and approved by Ofcom
-	Completing relevant due diligence checks including but not limited to:
-	Qualifications check
-	Right to work in the UK 
-	Design and delivery of an inclusive assessment and selection process which supports our diversity and inclusion aims
-	Production of a longlist of potential, proceedable (or otherwise) candidates, process to include:
-	Approaching potential, proceedable candidates and conducting pre-screening interviews (face to face or other means)
-	Managing essay distribution (where appropriate), chasing returns and providing shortlist with essays to Ofcom
-	Running each pathway assessment centre
-	Including notifying candidates of dates, managing communications between Ofcom and candidates (questions to be provided by Ofcom).
-	Candidate handling, including notifying candidates of any delays or changes to the timeline, informing unsuccessful candidates, notifying candidates of movement through the assessment stages.
-	Successfully offering the preferred candidate.
-	Weekly reporting including real time updates of diversity data of applicants per pathway (both verbal and written) throughout the process.
-	Be able to provide consistency of resource throughout the duration of the contract - Ofcom expect that the same individuals from the successful tenderer will be available throughout the duration of the contract, or for as much of the contract as possible, with outline plans for handling any handover of work to others to ensure, and demonstrate how, consistency of performance will be maintained.
-	Ofcom require the successful tenderer to pass on a copy of our privacy notice to any potential candidate and obtain each candidate's written permission for Ofcom to use their data in line with Ofcom's privacy notice in writing before submission to Ofcom.  Ofcom reserve the right to request any candidate's written authorisation of such a request.   

Services are expected to commence in October  2024   (service commencement date), with a period between contract signature and the service commencement date used for mobilising the service. Ofcom expects that the contractor will commence the mobilisation process by 1 August 2024

Any contract awarded following the conclusion of this procurement process will be for a period of 3 years until October 2027, e.g. for three seasons of graduate recruitment (2024

Additional information: 
Procurement documents can be found at the Ofcom Bravo Solutions procurement portal

column67: Call-Off for Technical Research and Economic Analysis
column68:
The Department for Levelling Up Housing and Communities requires technical and economic research to aid the development of housing policy across Government. Technical input includes an understanding of and access to chartered structural engineers, fire engineers, building services engineers, building surveyors, building control, expertise on accessibility and expertise on energy efficiency in addition to economic modelling and building regulation expertise.  This is not a call for competition, but an early notification that we intend to undertake engagement sessions in early February and also to provide time to providers to develop supply chains as required.  We intend to call-off via CCS Dynamic Purchasing System RM6126.  If you are not already on this DPS and you are interested in participating, please start making an application to become a DPS supplier.  

We are also hoping to speak with potential suppliers during engagement sessions in early February (to be held via teams).  We do not guarantee participation or invitation to attend a session.  If you are interested in early engagement, please e-mail SGB-Proc@levellingup.gov.uk
